Big day. Here's everything we announced → http://ubr.to/everyday-life-os

25% of total carbon emissions come from transportation. That is why today we are expanding our users’ access to cleaner modes of transport & reducing our carbon footprint by committing to power our US offices with 100% renewable energy by 2025. → http://ubr.to/sustainability
Today we’re proud to announce Uber’s partnership with @FeedingAmerica. We’ll be contributing over $1 million in cash and in-kind support. Learn more → https://ubr.to/feeding-america
This is the last straw Single-use items will no longer be included in your @ubereats order, unless requested. Find out more → http://ubr.to/food-access-sustainability
We’re developing @JUMPbyUber Charging Kiosks to make it even easier to keep the flowing.
Uber Transit is now live in: San Francisco Mexico City Paris And by the end of this year, Uber Transit will be live across 7 more cities Learn more → http://ubr.to/expanding-transit
.@RachaelRay’s best recipes are coming to @UberEats In select cities this fall you can order some of her favorite recipes and have them delivered to your door. Delish!
This just in: we’re making it easier for people with allergies and dietary restrictions to order on @UberEats. Learn more → http://ubr.to/food-access-sustainability
On-Trip Reporting is starting to roll out in October, an easy & discreet way to share a safety issue with us.
We’re developing enhanced facial verification technology to help further ensure that the driver who picks you up is the driver you see in the app.
Whether you’re riding in a or hopping on a , we want to help make sure you’re safe. That’s why today we’re announcing bike lane alerts will be rolled out to over 200 cities .
We’re piloting a new way for riders in select markets to contact 911 via text, straight from the Uber app in the event of an emergency.
To make sharing your PIN even easier, we’re testing wireless technology that will share your PIN directly with your driver.

Introducing Verify Your Ride with PIN — a new safety feature we're launching soon. Here's how it works: Riders will receive a unique 4-digit PIN for their ride in the app Rider shares PIN with driver The trip only begins in the app once the driver enters the correct PIN
Starting today we’re rolling out a new app experience so you can grab a ride and order @UberEats all in one app.
Stay tuned for news on our latest features

Chief Legal Officer @tonywest on our latest actions to help address the epidemic of sexual violence.

(6/6) Third, we commit to publishing a safety transparency report that will include data on sexual assaults and other incidents that occur on the Uber platform. Read more about our changes: https://ubr.to/lightson

(5/6) Second, survivors will now have the option to settle their claims with Uber without a confidentiality provision that prevents them from speaking about the facts of the sexual assault or harassment they suffered.
(4/6) First, we will no longer require Uber riders, drivers or employees to arbitrate their individual claims of sexual assault or harassment.
(3/6) Uber is not immune to this deeply rooted problem, and we believe that it is up to us to be a big part of the solution. With that in mind, we’re making some important changes today.

(2/6) And it’s clear that sexual violence remains a huge problem globally. The last 18 months have exposed a silent epidemic of sexual assault and harassment that haunts every industry and every community.
(1/6) Every day, Uber connects 15 million trips around the world. At that scale, our service ultimately reflects the world in which we operate—both the good and the bad.
